---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Frozen Uncovered — The Disney Deception — Nazaryah"
  description="Skadi, self-deification, and the highest-grossing cartoon about a woman becoming her own god — 'Let It Go' line by line."
>
  <div class="sw-wrap">

    <!-- ── HERO ── -->
    <section class="sw-hero">
      <a href="/disney" class="sw-back">&#8592; The Disney Deception</a>
      <p class="sw-label">&#8213; The Disney Deception &#8213;</p>
      <h1 class="sw-title">Frozen Uncovered</h1>
      <p class="sw-sub">
        Skadi, self-deification, and the highest-grossing cartoon about a woman becoming her own god
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- ── MODE BAR ── -->
    <div class="sw-mode-bar">
      <button id="btn-quick" class="sw-mode-btn sw-mode-active" data-tip="Fits between bath time and bedtime.">&#9654; Quick Read</button>
      <span class="sw-mode-divider">&#8213;</span>
      <button id="btn-full" class="sw-mode-btn" data-tip="This is why they invented coffee.">Full Study</button>
    </div>

    <!-- ── QUICK READ PANEL ── -->
    <div id="panel-quick">

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-kicker">If your daughters were born after 2010, they've probably sung 'Let It Go' more than a thousand times. Disney built a billion-dollar empire on that song. It won an Oscar. Have you ever sat down and actually listened to the words?</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">Let's Read the Song Together</p>
          <p>Here's what Elsa literally sings in the keynote number of the movie:</p>
          <ul class="sw-list">
            <li>"A kingdom of isolation, and it looks like I'm the queen."</li>
            <li>"Be the good girl you always have to be" — the old rules are oppression.</li>
            <li>"Let it go, let it go, can't hold it back anymore."</li>
            <li>"No right, no wrong, no rules for me. I'm free."</li>
            <li>"I am one with the wind and sky."</li>
            <li>"The past is in the past."</li>
            <li>"That perfect girl is gone."</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">Compare It to This</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Isaiah 14:13–14</p>
            <p>"For thou hast said in thine heart, I will ascend into heaven, I will exalt my throne above the stars of Elohim... I will be like the Most High."</p>
          </div>
          <p>That's Isaiah describing the Adversary's original rebellion. 'I will ascend. I will exalt. I will sit. I will be like the Most High.' It's the same structure as Let It Go. Both speeches say the same thing — I am my own god and I answer to no one.</p>
          <p>Elsa climbs a mountain (the biblical high place of false worship), builds herself a temple out of ice using her own power, throws off her old identity, and declares independence from 'right and wrong.' She didn't outgrow arbitrary rules. She threw off moral categories.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">But What About the Sister Bond?</p>
          <p>Lots of parents defend Frozen by pointing to the ending — Anna sacrifices herself for Elsa, it's sisterly love, not romantic love. Isn't that Christian?</p>
          <p>Look closely. Anna's sacrifice restores Anna, but it does not address Elsa's rebellion. Elsa never repents of the self-deification. She never returns to her responsibilities. She never apologizes for the chaos she caused. The rebellion is validated, not repented of.</p>
          <p>And Frozen 2 makes it worse. By the end of the sequel, Elsa has become a full-blown shamanic figure — the mediator between worlds, the spirit-bride of nature. What started as a girl with magical powers ends with her as a goddess. That's two films spent completing the apotheosis.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">What Frozen Teaches Your Daughters</p>
          <ul class="sw-list">
            <li>The power inside you is yours, and it's good.</li>
            <li>Rules about right and wrong are oppression.</li>
            <li>Parents and authorities who told you to hide yourself were wrong.</li>
            <li>The path to freedom is up the mountain, away from everyone.</li>
            <li>Build your own temple. You are your own queen.</li>
            <li>Spirits guide you to your true (divine) identity.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Ephesians 5:6</p>
            <p>"Let no man deceive you with vain words: for because of these things cometh the wrath of Elohim upon the children of disobedience."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="sw-footer-quote">
        <div class="sw-summary-block">
          <p class="sw-summary-label">&#9656; The Short Version</p>
          <p class="sw-summary-text">Frozen is the Isaiah 14:13-14 speech of the fallen one, rewritten in the voice of a young woman, scored by Broadway, and sold to children as the most empowering song ever written — with a plot that validates the rebellion and a sequel that completes the apotheosis.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="sw-cta-link" style="text-align:center; margin-top:1.5rem;">
          <button id="btn-full-cta" class="sw-mode-btn" style="font-size:0.75rem; letter-spacing:2px;">&#8594; Read the Full Study</button>
        </p>
      </section>

    </div><!-- /panel-quick -->

    <!-- ── FULL STUDY PANEL ── -->
    <div id="panel-full" style="display:none">

      <!-- ── SOURCE MATERIAL ── -->
      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">The Source Material: Skadi and the Snow Queen</p>
          <p>Elsa draws from two sources. The first is Skadi, the Norse goddess of winter and mountains — daughter of the giants who married into the Aesir, brought winter into the world, and lived in the cold mountains apart from human society. Arendelle's name is drawn from Norse place-names. The ice palace visual language is Skadi iconography.</p>
          <p>The second source is Hans Christian Andersen's 1844 "The Snow Queen" — written as a Christian allegory where the devil's magic mirror distorts perception and only Christ-like love can thaw a frozen heart. Disney kept the imagery and inverted the theology.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; The Inversion</p>
            <p>"Andersen wrote the Snow Queen as a figure whose ice-heart needed thawing by Christian love. Disney made the Snow Queen the protagonist and her ice palace the symbol of her liberation."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── LET IT GO LINE BY LINE ── -->
      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">'Let It Go' — A Line-by-Line Confession</p>
          <p>The film's centerpiece song is not a mood piece. It is a formal declaration of independence from every authority, every restraint, and every identity that came before. Read it carefully:</p>
          <ul class="sw-list">
            <li><strong>"Not a footprint to be seen"</strong> — isolation on the sacred mountain, the high place of pagan worship throughout Scripture (1 Kings 14:23, Jeremiah 2:20).</li>
            <li><strong>"A kingdom of isolation / And it looks like I'm the queen"</strong> — declares herself sovereign, no higher authority acknowledged.</li>
            <li><strong>"Be the good girl you always have to be... Conceal, don't feel"</strong> — external standards of virtue framed as oppression.</li>
            <li><strong>"No right, no wrong, no rules for me / I'm free"</strong> — the key confession. Explicit abandonment of moral categories.</li>
            <li><strong>"I am one with the wind and sky"</strong> — pantheistic identification with the natural order.</li>
            <li><strong>"I'm never going back / The past is in the past"</strong> — rejection of everything before. No repentance, only forward motion.</li>
            <li><strong>"I'll rise like the break of dawn... That perfect girl is gone"</strong> — the old self is dead, new self rises. Language of initiation.</li>
          </ul>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Isaiah 14:13–14</p>
            <p>"For thou hast said in thine heart, I will ascend into heaven, I will exalt my throne above the stars of Elohim... I will be like the Most High."</p>
          </div>
          <p>Compare it with 'Let It Go' and the structure is nearly identical. The ancient rebellion and the Disney anthem are saying the same thing with different words.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── THE ICE PALACE ── -->
      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">The Ice Palace as the New Temple</p>
          <p>When Elsa sings 'Let It Go,' she simultaneously constructs an ice palace with her own power. The building of a temple to one's own glory is the ancient pagan gesture — the tower at Babel, Nebuchadnezzar's statue at Dura, every Canaanite high place.</p>
          <p>She is her own god, her own priest, and her own temple.</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; The Pattern</p>
            <p>"Babel was built from mud. Elsa's palace is built from ice. The message is the same: I will build my own temple to my own glory, and no one will tell me no."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── SISTER BOND ── -->
      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">The Sister Bond as the Film's Redemption Narrative</p>
          <p>The self-sacrifice restores Anna but does not address Elsa's rebellion. Elsa's independence, abandonment of her throne, rejection of moral categories, and self-made temple — none of this is repented of.</p>
          <p>The only lesson is 'don't let your god-like powers accidentally hurt someone you love.' The theology of the chorus is never retracted.</p>
          <p>Andersen wrote that only Christ could thaw the frozen heart. Disney wrote that you can thaw it yourself if you love your sister enough.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── THE TROLLS ── -->
      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">The Trolls and Pagan Folk Magic</p>
          <p>Rock trolls practice folk healing and erase memories. They are presented as wise ancestors to be consulted. Kristoff calls them his "family" and they sing "Fixer Upper."</p>
          <div class="sw-scripture-block">
            <p class="sw-scripture-label">&#9656; Deuteronomy 18:10–12</p>
            <p>"There shall not be found among you any one that maketh his son or his daughter to pass through the fire, or that useth divination, or an observer of times, or an enchanter, or a witch, or a charmer, or a consulter with familiar spirits, or a wizard, or a necromancer. For all that do these things are an abomination unto Yahuah."</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── FROZEN 2 ── -->
      <section class="sw-section sw-section-alt">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">Frozen 2 and the Descent Deeper</p>
          <p>Elsa discovers she is descended from indigenous people whose spirits guide her. She journeys to an enchanted forest and encounters elemental spirits — fire, water, earth, wind. She discovers she is a fifth spirit. Her mother appears as a guiding ancestor from beyond death. By the end, Elsa is a full-blown shamanic figure — mediator between worlds.</p>
          <p>The self-deification trajectory started in the first film was completed in the second.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── WHAT FROZEN TEACHES ── -->
      <section class="sw-section">
        <div class="sw-prose">
          <p class="sw-section-heading">What Frozen Teaches a Child</p>
          <ul class="sw-list">
            <li>The powers inside you are your own, and they are good if you embrace them.</li>
            <li>Moral restraint is oppressive, and authentic freedom means leaving "right and wrong" behind.</li>
            <li>Parents and authorities who taught you to conceal your true self were wrong.</li>
            <li>The path of wholeness is to go up the mountain, build your own temple, and declare yourself queen.</li>
            <li>True love is whatever thaws whatever is frozen in you — no specific object required.</li>
            <li>Spirits and ancestors guide you to your true identity, which is ultimately divine.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Every one of these is Luciferian in structure, not metaphorically but precisely. The Adversary's original pitch in Genesis 3 was 'ye shall be as gods.' Frozen is that sermon, set to a score by a Broadway composer.</p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- ── SUMMARY ── -->
      <section class="sw-footer-quote">
        <div class="sw-summary-block">
          <p class="sw-summary-label">&#9656; Summary</p>
          <p class="sw-summary-text">Frozen is the Isaiah 14:13–14 speech of the fallen one, rewritten in the voice of a young woman, scored by Broadway, and sold to children as the most empowering song ever written — with a plot that validates the rebellion and a sequel that completes the apotheosis.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="sw-quote-text">"Let no man deceive you with vain words: for because of these things cometh the wrath of Elohim upon the children of disobedience."</p>
        <p class="sw-quote-ref">— Ephesians 5:6</p>
      </section>

    </div><!-- /panel-full -->

  </div>
</BaseLayout>

<script>
  const btnQuick = document.getElementById('btn-quick');
  const btnFull = document.getElementById('btn-full');
  const btnFullCta = document.getElementById('btn-full-cta');
  const panelQuick = document.getElementById('panel-quick');
  const panelFull = document.getElementById('panel-full');

  function showQuick() {
    panelQuick.style.display = '';
    panelFull.style.display = 'none';
    btnQuick.classList.add('sw-mode-active');
    btnFull.classList.remove('sw-mode-active');
    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: 'smooth' });
  }
  function showFull() {
    panelFull.style.display = '';
    panelQuick.style.display = 'none';
    btnFull.classList.add('sw-mode-active');
    btnQuick.classList.remove('sw-mode-active');
    window.scrollTo({ top: 0, behavior: 'smooth' });
  }

  btnQuick.addEventListener('click', showQuick);
  btnFull.addEventListener('click', showFull);
  if (btnFullCta) btnFullCta.addEventListener('click', showFull);
</script>

<style>
  .sw-wrap {
    background: linear-gradient(180deg, #060810 0%, #0c1020 20%, #080c18 100%);
    color: #f0e0bf;
    font-family: 'Crimson Pro', 'Crimson Text', Georgia, serif;
    min-height: 80vh;
  }

  .sw-mode-bar {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    justify-content: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    padding: 1rem 1.5rem;
    background: rgba(6, 8, 16, 0.97);
    border-bottom: 1px solid #141c38;
    position: sticky;
    top: 0;
    z-index: 10;
  }

  .sw-mode-divider {
    color: #1a2448;
    font-size: 0.65rem;
    letter-spacing: 4px;
  }

  .sw-mode-btn {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 0.65rem;
    letter-spacing: 2px;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    padding: 0.45rem 1.1rem;
    border-radius: 20px;
    border: 1px solid #2a3a60;
    background: transparent;
    color: #7a90c0;
    cursor: pointer;
    transition: all 0.2s;
    position: relative;
  }

  .sw-mode-btn:not(.sw-mode-active):hover {
    color: #c4a46b;
    border-color: rgba(60, 100, 186, 0.4);
    background: rgba(20, 40, 100, 0.1);
  }

  .sw-mode-active {
    background: rgba(30, 58, 139, 0.25);
    border-color: rgba(60, 100, 186, 0.45);
    color: #c4a46b;
  }

  .sw-mode-btn[data-tip]::after {
    content: attr(data-tip);
    position: absolute;
    bottom: calc(100% + 8px);
    left: 50%;
    transform: translateX(-50%);
    background: rgba(4, 6, 14, 0.97);
    color: #c4ad84;
    font-family: 'Crimson Pro', 'Crimson Text', Georgia, serif;
    font-size: 0.72rem;
    letter-spacing: 0.5px;
    text-transform: none;
    font-weight: normal;
    white-space: nowrap;
    padding: 0.35rem 0.8rem;
    border-radius: 4px;
    border: 1px solid #1a2448;
    opacity: 0;
    pointer-events: none;
    transition: opacity 0.2s;
    z-index: 20;
  }

  .sw-mode-btn:hover[data-tip]::after {
    opacity: 1;
  }

  .sw-hero {
    text-align: center;
    padding: 4rem 1.5rem 3.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #1a2448;
    background:
      radial-gradient(ellipse at 50% 0%, rgba(30, 50, 160, 0.2), transparent 70%),
      linear-gradient(180deg, #040610 0%, #0c1020 100%);
  }

  .sw-back {
    display: inline-block;
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 9px;
    letter-spacing: 2px;
    color: #3a4870;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    text-decoration: none;
    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;
    transition: color 0.2s;
  }
  .sw-back:hover { color: #c4a46b; }

  .sw-label {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 10px;
    letter-spacing: 4px;
    color: #4a5888;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
  }

  .sw-title {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: clamp(2.2rem, 6vw, 3.8rem);
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #f0e0bf;
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    line-height: 1.1;
  }

  .sw-sub {
    font-size: clamp(1rem, 2vw, 1.2rem);
    color: #c4a46b;
    font-style: italic;
    max-width: 560px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .sw-section {
    padding: 3.5rem 1.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid #101830;
  }

  .sw-section-alt {
    background: rgba(10, 20, 60, 0.15);
  }

  .sw-prose {
    max-width: 680px;
    margin: 0 auto;
    font-size: 1.125rem;
    line-height: 1.85;
    color: #d9c9a8;
  }

  .sw-prose p { margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
  .sw-prose p:last-child { margin-bottom: 0; }
  .sw-prose em { color: #c4a46b; font-style: italic; }
  .sw-prose strong { color: #e8d4a0; }

  .sw-kicker {
    font-style: italic;
    color: #c4a46b;
    border-left: 2px solid #1E3A8B;
    padding-left: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 1.75rem !important;
  }

  .sw-section-heading {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    letter-spacing: 1.5px;
    color: #c4a46b;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem !important;
  }

  .sw-scripture-block {
    border-left: 2px solid #1E3A8B;
    padding: 1rem 1.25rem;
    margin: 1.75rem 0;
    background: rgba(10, 20, 80, 0.15);
    border-radius: 0 4px 4px 0;
  }

  .sw-scripture-label {
    font-family: 'Cinzel', serif;
    font-size: 9px;
    letter-spacing: 2px;
    color: #3A5AAA;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    margin-bottom: 0.6rem !important;
  }

  .sw-list {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 1rem 0 1.5rem;
  }

  .sw-list li {
    padding: 0.6rem 0 0.6rem 1.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(20, 40, 100, 0.2);
    position: relative;
    color: #d9c9a8;
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
  }

  .sw-list li::before {
    content: '◆';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: #1E3A8B;
